<ce:abstract class="author"><ce:abstract-sec>
<ce:simple-para view="all">The activation performance of quenched Ti–28V–15Mn–10Cr alloy, surface modified by using ball-milling with 10<ce:hsp sp="0.25"></ce:hsp>wt.% LaNi<ce:inf loc="post">3.55</ce:inf>Co<ce:inf loc="post">0.75</ce:inf>Mn<ce:inf loc="post">0.4</ce:inf>Al<ce:inf loc="post">0.3</ce:inf> alloys was investigated. Compared with the plain Ti–28V–15Mn–10Cr alloy, the activation performance of the composite sample was remarkably improved. It was revealed that there is a layer of LaNi<ce:inf loc="post">3.55</ce:inf>Co<ce:inf loc="post">0.75</ce:inf>Mn<ce:inf loc="post">0.4</ce:inf>Al<ce:inf loc="post">0.3</ce:inf> nanoparticles with an average grain size about 30<ce:hsp sp="0.25"></ce:hsp>nm, covered on the surface of the composite sample. These nanoparticles accelerate the dissociation and absorption of hydrogen and then act as a window for hydrogen to enter the alloy bulk, resulting in an improvement of activation of the alloy.</ce:simple-para>
</ce:abstract-sec></ce:abstract>
<ce:keywords class="keyword" xml:lang="en">
